s use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Barnewall 1st Baron Trimlestown was born in 1424, in Crickstown, County Meath, Ireland, his father, Christopher Barnewall, was 34 and his mother, Matilda Drake, was 37. He married Elisabeth Brune about 1449, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1468, in County Meath, Ireland, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1424–1468":"1424–1468","1415–1501":"1415–1501","1422–1461":"1422–1461","1423–1501":"1423–1501","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1450–1511":"1450–1511","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1390–1446":"1390–1446","1388–1446":"1388–1446","before 1422":"enne 1422","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1424":"1424","1468":"1468","1446":"1446","1501":"1501","1511":"1511","1423":"1423","1422":"1422","about 1449":"umbes 1449","1388":"1388","12 October 1446":"12. oktoober 1446","1452":"1452","1430":"1430","1428":"1428","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Crickstown, County Meath, Ireland":"Crickstown, County Meath, Iirimaa","Crickstown Castle, Trimblestown, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Ireland, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Iirimaa","County Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Iirimaa","Trim, County Meath, Ireland":"Trim, County Mea